<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>nevadensis</i> and/or <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Amelanchier</i> <i>alnifolia</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cordulatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>velutinus</i>, <i>Chrysolepis</i> <i>sempervirens</i>, <i>Garrya</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>emarginata</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i>. Emergent conifer trees may be present at low cover including <i>Abies</i> <i>concolor</i>, <i>Abies</i> <i>magnifica</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>occidentalis</i> var. <i>occidentalis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>jeffreyi</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>lambertiana</i> and <i>Pinus</i> <i>monticola</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> > 30% relative cover within the shrub canopy (Lee 2004, Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Solomeshch et al. 2013).</li>
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy or co-dominant with <i>A. patula </i>(Solomeshch et al. 2013).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ridges and upper slopes that may be steep. Soils are shallow, can be acidic, and commonly derived from granitic or volcanic substrates.  </div>
</div>

        
