<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> is a long-lived, evergreen manzanita with bright green leaves that grows up to 2 m in height. Individuals in some portions of the species range have lignotubers; shrubs in other portions lack lignotubers. Plants can also reproduce by layering from the enlarged root crown. Shrubs produce abundant seed, which collects in duff and soil in a seed bank. Wildlife value the fruits and disperse the stones (Zimmerman 1991a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> characteristically forms stands in full sunlight in openings of coniferous forests, on recent and old burns, on rocky outcrops, and following logging. The species also occurs as scattered shrubs in forest understories. Self-perpetuating stands grow on skeletal or rocky soils, frequently on glaciated surfaces. Some stands exceed 100 years of age (Zimmerman 1991a). Stands can be seral, though long-persisting, on burned and logged sites with productive soils.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis</i> is a spreading, low-growing, evergreen manzanita that lacks lignotubers and, therefore, does not survive fire. Like <i>A. patula</i>, the stem roots where they make contact with the soil and establishes freely from seed following a fire. Wildlife browse seedlings but find mature plants unpalatable (Howard 1993d). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis</i> grows where overstory cover is sparse and does not tolerate low light levels. It is adapted to cool, dry sites at high elevations (up to 3,400 m). Stands of <i>A. nevadensis</i> are found in large openings of, or adjacent to, coniferous forest (Howard 1993d). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
