<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Arctostaphylos patula </i>plants are generally top-killed in burns, but they sprout vigorously from a root crown or buried lignotuber, if present. Abundant seedlings establish after a fire and sprouting plants quickly establish new crowns. After 10 years of growth, shrubs produce significant seed crops; sprouts take only 2 years. However, <i>A. patula </i>can experience highly consumptive, fatal burns when fuels are high and dry (Zimmerman 1991a).

Since <i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis</i> is lacking lignotubers it does not resprout after a fire. However, it does readily establish from seed post-fire (Howard 1993d).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (20-50 years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
