    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-g, Ai-u). Stands exist throughout the section excluding the broader low lying valleys. Most stands following fire and logging are transitional to mixed conifer and true fir forest types at montane and subalpine elevations, as at the Pearch Creek study area (Cheng 2004). Stands have been mapped in the Whiskeytown NM (Lee 2004). Persistent stands occur on open glaciated slopes and moraines at Sugar Creek RNA (Cheng 2004) and elsewhere in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf, Gi-n). Stands are post-fire and logging types in a matrix with pine forest alliances. Those in the Warner Mountains are transitional to <i>Abies concolor</i> forest types.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Stands are present in the higher elevations on Franciscan metasediments. Most stands follow fire and logging and are transitional to mixed conifer and true fir forest alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-h, Ej-u). Stands occur in all subsections but Sierra Valley. Most stands following fire and logging are transitional to mixed conifer and true fir forest alliances at montane and subalpine elevations. Persistent stands occur on open glaciated slopes and moraines in Clark Fork RNA (Cheng 2004), Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), Sequoia-Kings Canyon National Park (S. Haultain, pers. comm. 2005), and elsewhere in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands have been seen only in the southern portion of the ecoregion near <i>Pinus jefferyi</i> and <i>Pinus monophylla</i>  stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Be, Bh, Bm). Small localized stands occur in the western Transverse, San Bernardino, San Gabriel, and San Jacinto mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dc-d, Df-j, Dl-m). Stands occur in all subsections except the lower valleys. Extensive brush fields exist at base of Mount Shasta, near Burney, and in other areas following crown fires in the early twentieth century, and more recently after logging of pine and true fir forest types. Descriptions are available for the Antelope Creek Lakes RNA, Red Ridge-Red Fir RNA, and Green Island Lake RNA (Cheng 2004). Stands of <i>A. nevadensis</i> have been mapped in the Mill Creek watershed (Stillwater Sciences and AIS 2015).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> When stands of <i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> are subjected to fires, they quickly regenerate. Managers consider <i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> a detrimental in establishing fast growing conifers after logging and fires (Royce and Barbour 2001). Leaves are allelopathic when they decompose (Tinnin and Kirkpatrick 1985), and shrub roots effectively compete with conifer seedlings for soil water (Miller 1986). Managers use fire as a management tool to establish conifer stands at the expense of the shrubs by timing burns in the late spring or summer, when plants are actively growing and fuels are dry and consumable. However, on sites free of fire for long periods, <i>A. patula</i> facilitates conifer establishment in the filtered sunlight and high organic material supplied by the shrubs. 

Since <i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis</i> is lacking a lignotuber, fire will kill mature stands of <i>A. nevadensis</i> but it will regenerate quickly from seed and will colonize disturbed sites (Howard 1993d). People use <i>A. patula</i> and <i>A. nevadensis</i> in erosion control and bank stabilization (Zimmerman 1991a, Howard 1993d). </div>
</div>

    

    

